label.value: Prostate Cancer pMX TNM Finding v6

value.value: Prostate cancer in which the status of distant metastasis cannot be assessed. (from AJCC 6th Ed.)
Prostate cancer with no evidence of distant metastasis. (from AJCC 6th Ed.)
A blood vessel arising from the anterior side of the internal iliac artery that supplies the base of the bladder, prostate gland and seminal vesicles.
A blood vessel arising from the internal iliac artery that runs along the bladder with branches supplying the bladder.
A vein that represents a continuation of the angular vein and lies behind the facial artery.
A circumflex femoral vein that accompanies the medial circumflex femoral artery.
The vessels carrying deoxygenated blood on the upper side of the foot that originate from the dorsal digital vein creating the dorsal venous arch.
A cystic meningioma that grows within the cerebral hemispheres.
A blood vessel running parallel to the inferior pancreatico-duodenal artery that drains blood from the pancreas and duodenum into the splenic vein.
A vein that drains blood from the left kidney into the inferior vena cava.
A vein that drains blood from the right kidney into the inferior vena cava.
A vein that forms the spermatic plexus to drain the left testis into the left renal vein.
A vein that forms the spermatic plexus to drain the right testis into the inferior vena cava.
The blood vessels at the vertex and on either side of the head that drain deoxygenated blood into the pterygoid venous plexus.

A class of formulated therapeutic analogs of the endogenous gonadotropin that stimulates or promotes the function of the gonads.  Therapeutic gonadotropins are derived from animal or recombinant sources.  Gonadotropins include follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone and chorionic gonadotropin.  These agents stimulate discrete cellular components of the gonads, exerting effects in both males and females. (NCI04)
A papillary meningioma that affects the cerebellum.
A vein on the side of the head that merges with the internal maxillary vein to form the posterior facial vein.

Four muscles in the foot between the metatarsal bones extending down the medial and lateral sides of the proximal phalanx of the second toe and the lateral side of the proximal phalanx on the third and fourth toe.
Three small muscles located on the medial aspect of the third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal bones that facilitate adduction of the toes.

Four muscles in the hand between the metacarpal bones originating on the radial side of the metacarpal as well as the ulnar side of the previous metacarpal. The second and third interosseous muscles are inserted into the third proximal phalanx while the first is inserted into the second proximal phalanx and the fourth is inserted into the fourth proximal phalanx. These muscles act to abduct the fingers away from the middle finger.
Three small muscles, located on the second, fourth, and fifth fingers, on the palmar surfaces of the metacarpal bones facilitating the adduction, flexion and extension of the fingers.
The intrinsic muscles spanning the length of the tongue that move the tip of the tonge up and down.
Any of the intrinsic or extrinsic muscles of the tongue.
The intrinsic muscles spanning the width of the tongue that depress and flatten the tongue.

Either of the two types of ganglia found in the lining of the GI tract: the Myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus and the submucosal (Meissner) plexus, which are both small ganglia connected by thin, unmyelinated nerves.
A meningioma that affects the petrous apex.
A nucleus that is located in the olfactory tract.
A nucleus located in the middle hypothalamus in the most ventral part of the third ventricle near the entrance of the infundibular recess. Its small cells are in close contact with the ependyma.
The area in the cerebral cortex that receives and processes auditory input.
Part of the medial aspect of the cerebral cortex.
The dense or compact outer layer of tissue that covers the bone.
The medial margin of the thorax created by the seventh to tenth rib.

One of the dorsal column nuclei in the medulla oblongata, which is part of posterior column-medial lemniscus pathway, carrying sensory information from most the upper body to the contralateral thalamus via the medial lemniscus.
The skin covering the membrane that covers and protects each eye.
The skin covering the toes.
A meningioma that arises from the skull base.
The skin covering the fingers or appendages of the hand.

A series of nerves within the pelvis formed mostly by the extension of the hypogastric plexus and branches from the second, third and fourth sacral nerves. In males the inferior hypogastric nerve plexus is located on the sides of the rectum and in the female it is located on both the rectum and vagina.
An area of a long bone located at the junction of the diaphysis and epiphysis, which harbors the epiphyseal plate in immature bones.
A fibrous band located on the eyelid that connects the medial ends of the tarsal plates with the maxilla at the medial edge of the orbit.

An oval shaped cell group located in the subthalamus of the diencephalon, located between the medial part of the cerebral peduncle and the thalamus, and considered part of the functional basal ganglia.
Any one of the four lobes of the prostate gland including the anterior, lateral, median and posterior lobes.
The portion of the rib located at the posterior vertebral end, which is marked by a kidney-shaped articular surface.
The long, curved portion of the rib, which contains the intercostal vein, artery, and nerve in a groove found in the inferior margin.
A bony prominence located at the junction of the neck and the body of a rib, which articulates with the transverse processes of the adjacent thoracic vertebrae, ribs eleven and twelve excepted.
A meningioma that affects the ventricles of the brain.
The upper segment of the sternum, quadrangular in shape, as well as wider superiorly and narrower inferiorly. The sternal manubrium articulates with the clavicle and first two ribs.
